04049nam a22005535i 9780300163308DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20102010ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001633087 a10.12987/97803001633082doi  a(DE-B1597)486212  a(OCoLC)759397374  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aK3585b.K97 2010eb 7aPOL0440002bisacsh04a344.04/62221 aKysar, Douglas A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRegulating from Nowhere :bEnvironmental Law and the Search for Objectivity /cDouglas A. Kysar. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b10 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Regulating from Nowhere -- t1. Agency and Optimality -- t2. Prescription and Precaution -- tPart Two. The Perils of Prediction -- t3. Complexity and Catastrophe -- t4. Interests and Emergence -- tPart Three. The Environment of the Other -- t5. Other States -- t6. Other Generations -- t7. Other Forms of Life -- tPart Four. Our Environmental Future -- t8. Ecological Rationality -- t9. Environmental Constitutionalism -- tAppendix: The Environmental Possibilities Act -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawing insight from a diverse array of sources - including moral philosophy, political theory, cognitive psychology, ecology, and science and technology studies - Douglas Kysar offers a new theoretical basis for understanding environmental law and policy. He exposes a critical flaw in the dominant policy paradigm of risk assessment and cost-benefit analysis, which asks policymakers to, in essence, “regulate from nowhere.” As Kysar shows, such an objectivist stance fails to adequately motivate ethical engagement with the most pressing and challenging aspects of environmental law and policy, which concern how we relate to future generations, foreign nations, and other forms of life. Indeed, world governments struggle to address climate change and other pressing environmental issues in large part because dominant methods of policy analysis obscure the central reasons for acting to ensure environmental sustainability. To compensate for these shortcomings, Kysar first offers a novel defense of the precautionary principle and other commonly misunderstood features of environmental law and policy. He then concludes by advocating a movement toward environmental constitutionalism in which the ability of life to flourish is always regarded as a luxury we can afford.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental lawxPhilosophy. 0aEnvironmental lawzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030012001140uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016330840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300163308423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300163308/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY